I'm from Louisiana and know southern food, so had to see if the 10k review hype was real. Incredible cuisine is a dime a dozen in our state, from the NOLA gastro scene to gas station diners in bumpkin towns. To start, if you come on a weekday at 10-11a you will evade the crowds and get seated / served immediately. I ordered the coffee, orange juice, cheese grits, and eggs benedict. Overall would rank this an 'OK' (3.5 stars) dining experience. I would not come here if I had to endure a weekend wait and risk being panhandled in the tenderloin. The good: *The coffee - classic NOLA chicory coffee; it was hot, freshly brewed, with ideal chicory aftertaste. 'Community Coffee' canisters line the display shelves, so it's nice to see that mark of legitimacy. *Orange juice - incredible. Maybe they're procuring oranges from a holy grove. Or holly grove? *Biscuit under the eggs benedict - crispy exterior and a soft pillowy interior. Honestly the biscuit alone made me wish I ordered biscuits and gravy instead. *Cheese grits - so good! huge shareable portion for $4 for a 'side'. cheese is both baked into the grits and melted on top, they didn't congeal and stayed hot 15 mins into the meal. The not good: **Service - Def no southern hospitality to match the food .They weren't that busy but my waitress slammed things on my table, no greetings/cordialities. To their credit, another lady/man (?) also helped, he/she was a sweetie. **No to go cups for the coffee!!! I had almost 3/4 of my coffee left and needed to dash to make sure the tenderloin hobos weren't violating my car. If you want a to go cup, you pay $3.50, effectively the cost of another cup. No thx, stingedogs. **Hollandaise on eggs benedict -Looked/ tasted like kraft thousand island dressing; weirdly sweet. Didn't even finish the dish because of this sauce. Will prob just try the other southern places in SF (or just fly home) when my next craving hits.

A perfect place to grab brunch! I'm so happy that Brenda's French Soul Food lives up to all the amped up reviews. We arrived probably at the most inopportune time - peak lunch rush hour during the weekend on Sunday. There was a mob plus a snaking line of folks waiting to be seated. Maybe about 20 or so parties ahead of us. We debated whether the long wait (ended up being close to an hour) was worth it... But after reading all the reviews and smelling the delicious kitchen scents wafting out, we decided to stick around. I'm sure glad we did! Once seated inside, service is prompt and friendly. Mostly table seating with one bar strip. Sweet Watermelon Iced Tea || $3.50 Not too sweet - a perfectly refreshing watermelon basil juice plus sweet tea drink to compliment your meal. Free refills provided so drink to your heart's content :) Beignets Flight || $12 Worth getting if you want to share/try all the 4 different beignets available. There's crawfish, apple, chocolate, and plain. The crawfish one comes topped with a Cajun seasoning that has the slightest tingle & is stuffed with the creamiest sauce coating tender crawfish. The apple, chocolate, and plain ones are great if you have a sweet tooth, but not quite as unique as the crawfish one. Definitely give the crawfish beignets a try! Eggs Benedict Fried Chicken || $14.50 The fried chicken is oh so juicy and tender with the perfect crunchy exterior. Light seasoning of black pepper and salt - I noticed some other yelpers who thought the seasoning to be too bland, but I actually appreciated the simplicity of this good ole fried chicken. The cream biscuits are amazing - probably the lightest, fluffiest biscuits I've ever had with a flaky crumb and a rich taste of cream. Pairs perfectly with the chicken, poached eggs, and spiced Cajun hollandaise sauce with a sprinkle of green onions. Eggs Benedict Florentino || $13 A classic eggs benedict dish with spinach, mushrooms, poached eggs, Cajun spiced hollandaise sauce with green onions. Yumm. The eggs benedict dishes come with a side of either grits or potato hash. The grits are creamy with a rich pool of butter on top. Pairs well if you like eating it with your biscuit, eggs, etc. The potatoes are also a classic - Cajun spiced. So happy I got to try the food here! Would recommend stopping by if you're in the area - but plan to come early or maybe at a less busy time if you don't want to wait long.

Brenda's crawfish beignets are to die for. They are warm, hearty, fluffy pillows of dough, generously filled with delicious creamy crawfish. I will make the trek to SF just for these. There's always a long line on weekends, so try to come as early as possible (9-10AM is best). Everything about Brenda's is inviting and comforting, from the service to the food, to the ambience. Other than the beignets, I also recommend the fried catfish benedict. Poached eggs and fried fish make an amazing combo, and it's quite a generous portion as well. I was really sleepy after my 9AM meal here, but it's honestly a wonderful feeling to have after experiencing Brenda's fatty, buttery, coma-inducing food. I'll definitely keep coming back for more!

There isn't much else to say about Brenda's that hasn't already been said by the other 10,000 (!!!) reviewers here. At the very least, I can confirm that most of those taste buds are sane and blessed to have tried this Southern classic, hanging on the edge of the Tenderloin. Brenda's is absolutely mouthwatering Cajun and Southern food at its finest. Two friends and I came to Brenda's on a Friday evening in July, surprised to find that there were hardly any people ahead of us. You scribble your name down on a chalkboard, clap the dust off your hands in front of the cramped waiting area, and wait for the hosts to call you. It took less than 10 minutes to grab a teeny tiny table for three in their dining room. Our servers were out quick with drink orders -- three watermelon iced teas -- and took down our dishes. My friends ordered the chicken etouffee and BFC platter with extra collard greens. I had the shrimp and grits with a side of fried chicken. Everything you've heard about the fried chicken is true. Gloriously crisp and craggy, this is the stuff that Jollibee can't quite compete with. I felt like I had to knock a star off for the embarrassingly small drumstick I received for $3. That drumstick must've been brined in the buttermilk from the first cow for it to be that much. But it was tasty, so I can't complain that much. As for my shrimp and grits? Creamy, buttery and spiced just right with the wicked tomato sauce they ladle on top. At disappointing brunches I've had since, I've dreamt of that tangy tomato sauce. The shrimp was cooked perfectly to boot. I took some home because I was so full and the leftovers were surprisingly good the day after. If I had the room for dessert, I would've done it. Brenda's is one of the only places in San Francisco that serves bread pudding, which is such a heavy but yummy treat. Come hungry.

    I'm from Louisiana and know southern food, so had to see if the 10k review hype was real. Incredible cuisine is a dime a dozen in our state, from the NOLA gastro scene to gas station diners in bumpkin towns.

    To start, if you come on a weekday at 10-11a you will evade the crowds and get seated / served immediately.

    I ordered the coffee, orange juice, cheese grits, and eggs benedict. Overall would rank this an 'OK' (3.5 stars) dining experience. I would not come here if I had to endure a weekend wait and risk being panhandled in the tenderloin.

    The good:
    *The coffee - classic NOLA chicory coffee; it was hot, freshly brewed, with ideal chicory aftertaste. 'Community Coffee' canisters line the display shelves, so it's nice to see that mark of legitimacy.  

    *Orange juice - incredible. Maybe they're procuring oranges from a holy grove. Or holly grove?

    *Biscuit under the eggs benedict - crispy exterior and a soft pillowy interior. Honestly the biscuit alone made me wish I ordered biscuits and gravy instead.

    *Cheese grits - so good! huge shareable portion for $4 for a 'side'. cheese is both baked into the grits and melted on top, they didn't congeal and stayed hot 15 mins into the meal.

    The not good:
    **Service - Def no southern hospitality to match the food .They weren't that busy but my waitress slammed things on my table, no greetings/cordialities. To their credit, another lady/man (?) also helped, he/she was a sweetie.

    **No to go cups for the coffee!!!
    I had almost 3/4 of my coffee left and needed to dash to make sure the tenderloin hobos weren't violating my car. If you want a to go cup, you pay $3.50, effectively the cost of another cup. No thx, stingedogs.

    **Hollandaise on eggs benedict -Looked/ tasted like kraft thousand island dressing; weirdly sweet. Didn't even finish the dish because of this sauce.

    Will prob just try the other southern places in SF (or just fly home) when my next craving hits.

It's been so long since I came for brunch, so I am not sure if the menu is a little different on weekdays. I think the quality depends on what item on the menu you get. The oyster po boy and shrimp and grits were good  and so were the crawfish beignets.

    Overall, I would eat here again if I was in the neighborhood and it was a weekday but not sure if I would ever do the weekend wait again.

    A perfect place to grab brunch! I'm so happy that Brenda's French Soul Food lives up to all the amped up reviews.

    We arrived probably at the most inopportune time - peak lunch rush hour during the weekend on Sunday. There was a mob plus a snaking line of folks waiting to be seated. Maybe about 20 or so parties ahead of us.

    We debated whether the long wait (ended up being close to an hour) was worth it... But after reading all the reviews and smelling the delicious kitchen scents wafting out, we decided to stick around. I'm sure glad we did!

    Once seated inside, service is prompt and friendly. Mostly table seating with one bar strip.

    Sweet Watermelon Iced Tea || $3.50
    Not too sweet - a perfectly refreshing watermelon basil juice plus sweet tea drink to compliment your meal. Free refills provided so drink to your heart's content :)

    Beignets Flight || $12
    Worth getting if you want to share/try all the 4 different beignets available. There's crawfish, apple, chocolate, and plain. The crawfish one comes topped with a Cajun seasoning that has the slightest tingle & is stuffed with the creamiest sauce coating tender crawfish. The apple, chocolate, and plain ones are great if you have a sweet tooth, but not quite as unique as the crawfish one. Definitely give the crawfish beignets a try!

    Eggs Benedict Fried Chicken || $14.50
    The fried chicken is oh so juicy and tender with the perfect crunchy exterior. Light seasoning of black pepper and salt - I noticed some other yelpers who thought the seasoning to be too bland, but I actually appreciated the simplicity of this good ole fried chicken. The cream biscuits are amazing - probably the lightest, fluffiest biscuits I've ever had with a flaky crumb and a rich taste of cream. Pairs perfectly with the chicken, poached eggs, and spiced Cajun hollandaise sauce with a sprinkle of green onions.

    Eggs Benedict Florentino || $13
    A classic eggs benedict dish with spinach, mushrooms, poached eggs, Cajun spiced hollandaise sauce with green onions. Yumm.

    The eggs benedict dishes come with a side of either grits or potato hash. The grits are creamy with a rich pool of butter on top. Pairs well if you like eating it with your biscuit, eggs, etc. The potatoes are also a classic - Cajun spiced.

    So happy I got to try the food here! Would recommend stopping by if you're in the area - but plan to come early or maybe at a less busy time if you don't want to wait long.

    There isn't much else to say about Brenda's that hasn't already been said by the other 10,000 (!!!) reviewers here. At the very least, I can confirm that most of those taste buds are sane and blessed to have tried this Southern classic, hanging on the edge of the Tenderloin. Brenda's is absolutely mouthwatering Cajun and Southern food at its finest.

    Two friends and I came to Brenda's on a Friday evening in July, surprised to find that there were hardly any people ahead of us. You scribble your name down on a chalkboard, clap the dust off your hands in front of the cramped waiting area, and wait for the hosts to call you. It took less than 10 minutes to grab a teeny tiny table for three in their dining room. Our servers were out quick with drink orders -- three watermelon iced teas -- and took down our dishes. My friends ordered the chicken etouffee and BFC platter with extra collard greens. I had the shrimp and grits with a side of fried chicken.

    Everything you've heard about the fried chicken is true. Gloriously crisp and craggy, this is the stuff that Jollibee can't quite compete with. I felt like I had to knock a star off for the embarrassingly small drumstick I received for $3. That drumstick must've been brined in the buttermilk from the first cow for it to be that much. But it was tasty, so I can't complain that much.

    As for my shrimp and grits? Creamy, buttery and spiced just right with the wicked tomato sauce they ladle on top. At disappointing brunches I've had since, I've dreamt of that tangy tomato sauce. The shrimp was cooked perfectly to boot. I took some home because I was so full and the leftovers were surprisingly good the day after.

    If I had the room for dessert, I would've done it. Brenda's is one of the only places in San Francisco that serves bread pudding, which is such a heavy but yummy treat. Come hungry.
